324
00:54:01.090 --> 00:54:12.769
David Thomson: And as you see here at ExamTip, if you're going to take one of these certification exams, CBAP or CCPA particularly, it's good to know how these apply to all of each, the knowledge areas in the BABAC, but…

325
00:54:13.760 --> 00:54:33.759
David Thomson: By way of change, when you're thinking about, illustration and collaboration, the change part is you're identifying the change and the stakeholder concerns about it. You know, as I mentioned before, understanding what their… what their motivation is, what maybe their concerns are about the change, and realizing that this is a change.

326
00:54:33.880 --> 00:54:44.100
David Thomson: to them, and sometimes the changes are difficult. You think about the need, you need to understand what the need is. Sometimes it's a matter of eliciting the need.

327
00:54:44.190 --> 00:54:55.740
David Thomson: You know, sometimes the need can be super high level. Oh, we need this software. Why do we need this software? Oh, because it'll save us time. Okay, how will it save you time? You know, digging into the, you know, over to the…

328
00:54:56.000 --> 00:55:13.410
David Thomson: five whys, you know, if you… if you ask why five times, you usually get to the root of the… of the… the issue. Well, we need to be first. Well, we need, you know, you get… you continue to dig down, to really understand the core needs. That really helps with elicitation.

329
00:55:13.670 --> 00:55:21.949
David Thomson: The stakeholders, obviously, in this situation, you're really working with the stakeholders quite a bit, and that… in the core concept model.

330
00:55:22.250 --> 00:55:25.960
David Thomson: You're involving them, you're managing their collaboration with them.

331
00:55:26.290 --> 00:55:44.540
David Thomson: The value is you're, you're thinking about the value of the information that's gathered. You know, the info… when you do elicitation and collaboration, or any of these… any of these elicitation exercises, the… the… the data and the information you get

332
00:55:44.890 --> 00:55:55.939
David Thomson: from that is really gold, if you think about it, hopefully gold. You know, that's very, very valuable to the success of the initiative that you're working on.

333
00:55:55.950 --> 00:56:11.230
David Thomson: So, you know, what you're doing there is where you're not only identifying the value proposition for what the initiative needs, but the value to your stakeholders. And sometimes it's a matter of

334
00:56:11.480 --> 00:56:15.419
David Thomson: communicating that value to your stakeholders as well. They may not quite see it.

335
00:56:16.370 --> 00:56:17.919
David Thomson: And they may not see it.

336
00:56:18.130 --> 00:56:22.779
David Thomson: From the perspective, maybe the larger perspective of the organization itself.

337
00:56:23.570 --> 00:56:25.670
David Thomson: The context is…

338
00:56:25.860 --> 00:56:40.799
David Thomson: how you're using those elicitation techniques to identify, as this is the context of the change, or, you know, in what context are we… are we utilizing this? Maybe, how are we slicing this, or how are we approaching this? What context is it?

339
00:56:41.630 --> 00:56:43.569
David Thomson: And the solution itself.

340
00:56:43.790 --> 00:56:46.990
David Thomson: You know, your… You're maybe not…

341
00:56:47.880 --> 00:56:55.930
David Thomson: at this point, thinking about what the solution is. Hopefully, you're not solutioning as you're gathering requirements, but you're thinking about how the illustration

342
00:56:56.100 --> 00:57:07.330
David Thomson: The information you've gotten through elicitation will be kind of formatted, prepping to help find the appropriate solutions, and maybe some solutions.

343
00:57:07.470 --> 00:57:09.909
David Thomson: You know, a lot of us have been on projects where

344
00:57:10.040 --> 00:57:25.160
David Thomson: the solution is in front of us, we need to find out how we're going to utilize the solution. We're going to implement the… this is our… our need is we need to implement this solution that my golf buddy sold me on at the golf match yesterday.

345
00:57:25.160 --> 00:57:34.230
David Thomson: And then we have to find a need to justify it, so your job as business analyst is to justify this solution that, maybe the executive has purchased

346
00:57:34.310 --> 00:57:36.440
David Thomson: Without really thinking through things.

347
00:57:40.260 --> 00:57:58.669
David Thomson: that rarely happens. So… but anyway, yeah, this is… it's important to think about that back. If you look at, any of the other knowledge areas, and we go through this every time we go through one of these study sessions, specifically about a knowledge area, we'll review that. And it's good to know these days, especially if you're planning to take it.

348
00:57:59.040 --> 00:58:00.070
David Thomson: a test.

349
00:58:00.200 --> 00:58:13.829
David Thomson: Let's see, I'll move to this slide. That's all the real data we're covering tonight. Our next study session, as I mentioned, is requirements lifecycle Management. That'll be in September.

350
00:58:14.150 --> 00:58:21.490
David Thomson: And we don't have a date on that yet, I don't think, but … watch for that. It'll… it's a good one. Requirements lifecycle management is…

351
00:58:21.930 --> 00:58:41.010
David Thomson: One of my favorite. I say that about every one of them, but it's one of my favorite, knowledge areas. Definitely some great stuff to learn from there. So with that, anybody have any questions about elicitation and collaboration? Anybody want to talk about anything? Or maybe even, you know, some of their… some of your experience with elicitation and collaboration?

352
00:58:43.560 --> 00:59:02.890
Sheri Smith: It was affirming for me hearing you talk about getting clarity, and still at that point, maybe there were miscommunications initially, because I guess whenever I get a elicitation, whenever I'm doing elicitation with stakeholders, and I miss something at the beginning stage, I guess I feel like I let them down, or like.

353
00:59:03.090 --> 00:59:06.680
Sheri Smith: It's on me for not getting 100%, so…

354
00:59:06.800 --> 00:59:09.410
Sheri Smith: It was just affirming to hear you talk about that.

355
00:59:09.700 --> 00:59:19.160
David Thomson: Yeah, I think that… that happens to all of us, really, you know, it's like… and you… and you have to ask, do I have everything? And maybe your stakeholder's tired, they don't want to…

356
00:59:19.180 --> 00:59:37.739
David Thomson: Now, I'm sure they don't look forward to… they want to move to the next meeting, or they want to get to the end of the day, and maybe they haven't thought through it, and so we can't… we can't put that on ourselves, but what we can do is just be available and be, you know, here's what I heard. Does this look good to you? A lot of times, you do have to put the onus on them to say.

357
00:59:37.740 --> 00:59:41.520
David Thomson: You signed off on this, this is what we heard, you know, …

358
00:59:41.700 --> 00:59:56.460
David Thomson: Our job isn't to, you know, dig up the world and find every little thing, you know? You need the help of the stakeholders. That's why cultivating that stakeholder relationship is really important. But yeah, confirming those results is really…

359
00:59:56.840 --> 01:00:14.970
David Thomson: really key, and that's… I feel that is liberating, really, you know, rather than it being on you, and say, okay, this is what I heard, here you go, is this right? You know, you're the business expert, you know… this is your… this is your area of expertise. Am I missing anything? Do I understand this correctly?

360
01:00:15.110 --> 01:00:15.930
David Thomson: …

361
01:00:16.090 --> 01:00:31.130
David Thomson: I told somebody, about a year or two ago, I said, I like being a business analyst because I can be dumb. I can ask the dumb questions. I can say, wait, wait, I don't understand. And I… and I say that quite a… quite a bit, you know, I'm sorry, I don't understand this. Can you help me?

362
01:00:31.270 --> 01:00:32.300
David Thomson: And, …

363
01:00:32.400 --> 01:00:50.109
David Thomson: you know, it's okay to be that person that doesn't understand, because that helps you. A lot of times, when a stakeholder wants to talk you through that, they start thinking about it in a different way, and they think, well, you know, I've been doing this for 20 years, I know this as a stakeholder, this is my area of expertise.

364
01:00:50.120 --> 01:00:57.949
David Thomson: I can't… I can't skip all these little things to help somebody understand. So, yeah, I think that that's a key part, is just making sure that you're…

365
01:00:58.130 --> 01:01:04.319
David Thomson: hey, do I have a shrine? Am I missing anything? That's a key added step, so thank you for mentioning.

366
01:01:09.140 --> 01:01:10.630
David Thomson: Any other thoughts?

367
01:01:12.350 --> 01:01:19.319
Moe Raine: Yeah, hi, Dave. David, sorry. I had a question. Yeah, I was working on a project where

368
01:01:19.560 --> 01:01:32.329
Moe Raine: I joined in the middle, and the requirements were already gathered, and we're going through analysis and design, and when we get to configuration walkthrough… so, the business comes with new business rules?

369
01:01:32.460 --> 01:01:35.520
David Thomson: Because initially, when the requirements were gathered.

370
01:01:35.770 --> 01:01:43.560
Moe Raine: They were thinking or looking at things from how the system functions now, but then when they have a better view of how the system works, and…

371
01:01:43.600 --> 01:02:00.049
Moe Raine: kind of looking at things from a second pair of eyes. Oh, maybe we can do this, maybe we can add these rules to automate things more, and we were working with a third-party vendor, Cot Solution, and they kept slapping us with, you know, PCR on every single thing. Now.

372
01:02:00.240 --> 01:02:01.250
Moe Raine: how…

373
01:02:01.390 --> 01:02:13.460
Moe Raine: can we avoid… is there a way to reduce it or minimize that happening? Like, if in the future I'm working on a project when I'm gathering requirements, like.

374
01:02:13.780 --> 01:02:16.559
Moe Raine: Anything in your experience that would be useful?

375
01:02:17.580 --> 01:02:24.030
David Thomson: Yeah, I have a couple of thoughts on that, and this is very relevant to something I've gone through before, …

376
01:02:24.340 --> 01:02:27.170
David Thomson: You know, it's… it's a matter of…

377
01:02:27.230 --> 01:02:33.579
David Thomson: you know, when you think about system replacement, let's say we have an old system or a current system, the current state.

378
01:02:33.620 --> 01:02:46.910
David Thomson: you use it a certain way, and then the new system has new capabilities, new functions, things that maybe it's hard to visualize. You know, I have trouble… when I built the house many, many years ago.

379
01:02:46.950 --> 01:03:06.910
David Thomson: well, I had a house built, I should say. I just couldn't see it. I thought, oh man, this house is gonna be small. I didn't… I couldn't think outside of the blueprint itself, you know? It was hard to think about what that looks like. What I needed to do was go to one that had already been built, the same model, and that helped me kind of see it better. You know, so I…

380
01:03:06.950 --> 01:03:08.420
David Thomson: That said, I think…

381
01:03:08.610 --> 01:03:18.830
David Thomson: If it's at all possible to do, like, a prototype or proof of concept to say, this is, you know, to get the stakeholders thinking about, oh, we can do it this way.

382
01:03:19.230 --> 01:03:28.820
David Thomson: That not always is an easy part, because that in and of itself, especially if you're working with a third-party vendor who's an implementation partner, for example, they're…

383
01:03:29.090 --> 01:03:40.190
David Thomson: They don't… they would rather just go to the implementation phase. They don't want to do a proof-of-concept phase, typically, or that could be very costly. So, as much as possible.

384
01:03:40.340 --> 01:03:53.209
David Thomson: you know, that continuous feedback, particularly through the build process. If you're doing more of an agile approach to the build, you know, bringing your stakeholders in and making sure that they're participating.

385
01:03:53.260 --> 01:03:58.030
David Thomson: That doesn't necessarily mean that… that there won't be new requirements.

386
01:03:58.050 --> 01:04:13.690
David Thomson: But if you can do, like, a prototype phase, and as much as possible, allow them to think outside of the box, you know, don't think so much about your current system. Let's focus on… you know, there could be some core requirements that you have on the current system that get replied to the new system.

387
01:04:13.820 --> 01:04:15.380
David Thomson: But, …

388
01:04:15.550 --> 01:04:24.080
David Thomson: You know, let's think outside of the box, and really help them to understand, what the capabilities of the new system might be.

389
01:04:24.170 --> 01:04:41.109
David Thomson: You know, let's don't think of it… think of the perfect world in this new system, how you would like it, versus being stuck in, you know, we wanted to do this, what it's done for 10 or 15 years, or whatever, in the current system. As much as possible, like I said, a lot of times, I…

390
01:04:41.470 --> 01:04:42.990
David Thomson: At the very least.

391
01:04:43.090 --> 01:04:55.229
David Thomson: bringing them along for feedback, continuous feedback during the build process. You know, hey, tweak that screen, or hey, we want to see that as a drop-down instead of a radio button, or whatever.

392
01:04:55.340 --> 01:05:03.079
David Thomson: That's helpful, but if possible, do a proof of concept, or get them as much involved in thinking about that future state as much as possible.

393
01:05:04.040 --> 01:05:05.620
David Thomson: Does that… does that make sense?

394
01:05:05.620 --> 01:05:07.550
Moe Raine: Yeah, absolutely. Thank you.

395
01:05:09.620 --> 01:05:10.310
David Thomson: Sure.

396
01:05:11.360 --> 01:05:13.519
David Thomson: There's no easy answer for that, I will say.

397
01:05:14.830 --> 01:05:25.960
David Thomson: Especially, as you said, you're dropped in the middle of it, you know? Like, here are the requirements that somebody got for us, you know?

398
01:05:25.960 --> 01:05:36.300
David Thomson: Why didn't those meet… you know, why aren't those relevant to our… the system where they're doing? Well, gee, we had this black box out there that we had no idea how it worked.

399
01:05:36.380 --> 01:05:43.100
David Thomson: You know, there's sometimes that's a slippery slope, but as much as possible, learning about the capabilities of the new system.

400
01:05:43.240 --> 01:05:50.189
David Thomson: And… and maybe getting… getting hands-on as much as possible. UAT is a very valuable

401
01:05:50.520 --> 01:05:57.309
David Thomson: I feel like an iterative UAT user acceptance testing is extremely valuable because

402
01:05:57.430 --> 01:06:16.470
David Thomson: the users… the end users ultimately will be able to give feedback, as they're going through it. They're testing, that didn't work. Oh, we actually wanted to see this, and you can go through and say, okay, here are our top enhancements that we want to see on this. Maybe those can be fit in, you know, before you go live.

403
01:06:16.560 --> 01:06:30.469
David Thomson: maybe those are things that are kind of at the top of your backlog, your product backlog, and say, okay, well, I know it doesn't do this right now, but it will, after we go live, we'll work on these other things. Sometimes that can be helpful as well.

404
01:06:33.130 --> 01:06:35.549
David Thomson: A lot of times, it depends on the approach of the…

405
01:06:36.520 --> 01:06:47.140
David Thomson: of the initiative, whether it's, like, a waterfall implementation, okay, well, it's… everything's in the books already, or it's an agile, well, we're gonna tweak this as we go along, and…

406
01:06:47.290 --> 01:06:49.300
David Thomson: And make it better and better as it goes.

407
01:06:51.840 --> 01:06:59.099
David Thomson: hopefully more and more, initiatives are like that. I'm seeing that over the past few years, more agile approach.

408
01:07:02.340 --> 01:07:04.610
David Thomson: Yeah, great, great question. Thanks for it.

409
01:07:04.950 --> 01:07:05.700
David Thomson: Escalant.

410
01:07:07.580 --> 01:07:08.809
Moe Raine: My pleasure. You know?

411
01:07:09.010 --> 01:07:09.929
David Thomson: Oh yeah, sure.

412
01:07:12.310 --> 01:07:13.679
David Thomson: You buy anything else?

413
01:07:13.680 --> 01:07:15.819
Moe Raine: Can I ask a follow-up question?

414
01:07:15.820 --> 01:07:16.250
David Thomson: Sure.

415
01:07:16.250 --> 01:07:35.680
Moe Raine: Sometime, you know, when it comes to requirement solicitation, some of the stakeholders I work, they're super technical, and then there's a bit of a language barrier involved as well. And when I ask a very specific, targeted questions, the conversation goes off to, like, a tangent, like, completely, and

416
01:07:35.780 --> 01:07:37.110
Moe Raine: …

417
01:07:37.520 --> 01:07:55.930
Moe Raine: I don't know if you had experience… by the way, I live in Toronto, so I don't know if you had similar experiences, and what would be a respectful way to bring them back to the… what the focus is, what the purpose of the session is, and how to, yeah, get it done.

418
01:07:56.330 --> 01:08:08.050
David Thomson: Yeah, that's a great point. You know, I think that goes back to the preparation for elicitation exercise. It's, not always… not always easy to do that, but as much as possible.

419
01:08:08.150 --> 01:08:21.179
David Thomson: You know, particularly if someone who is deeply more technical, you know, kind of prepping them and saying, hey, you're… you're very technical, and we appreciate that, and we like that feedback, but, …

420
01:08:21.399 --> 01:08:41.040
David Thomson: keep in mind, the other stakeholders that will be participating in this exercise may not have your depth of knowledge on this. So, you know, I think it'd just be… I like the idea of just being open and honest and saying, hey, let's try to keep it at an understandable level, and don't get down to the molecular level with how everything works.

421
01:08:41.100 --> 01:08:55.609
David Thomson: sometimes it might need… you might need to go there. They might help to bring you that clarity. I think it's a matter of also, you know, making very clear what the agenda is, what… what's in scope and what's not in scope. You know, we're going to talk about this topic

422
01:08:55.640 --> 01:09:14.979
David Thomson: at this level, maybe, it might be helpful to say, we're not going to go into the minutiae of how, let's say, system-to-system integration. We're not going to go to the level of the JSON values, or whatever, you know, what XML is being transmitted. We're not going to go to that level. We're going to keep it at the very high

423
01:09:15.010 --> 01:09:16.340
David Thomson: object level.

424
01:09:16.399 --> 01:09:20.399
David Thomson: And, and just identify some key characteristics.

425
01:09:20.510 --> 01:09:25.220
David Thomson: As much as you can set those ground rules and say, okay, well.

426
01:09:25.540 --> 01:09:33.269
David Thomson: once we've done this, and everybody's got a… and I think… this is a phrase I like to use a lot… a common understanding of what it is.

427
01:09:33.380 --> 01:09:45.269
David Thomson: Keeping at that, there will be opportunities to dig more into those deeper… deeper dives, maybe with a subset of stakeholders, if not every stakeholder is needed.

428
01:09:46.410 --> 01:09:58.619
David Thomson: But I think establishing those ground rules as much as possible on the front end is a good practice. Doesn't always work, of course. It's hard to keep people from going deep. And a lot of times, these sessions, these workshops.

429
01:09:58.700 --> 01:10:05.880
David Thomson: To be honest, there'll be people in there that just want to show off everything that they know, and like to hear themselves talk.

430
01:10:05.940 --> 01:10:20.809
David Thomson: And so, you might just have to kind of, as facilitator, kind of, let's bring it back up to this level, and let's talk about that. You know, that can be a challenge, but it's definitely… in your role as a facilitator, it's something

431
01:10:21.000 --> 01:10:36.480
David Thomson: you… you might want to… I better… I better work with this person on the front end to make sure that they understand that… what's in scope and what's out of scope, and where we want to keep it level-wise. I think you… I think you can do that, and that… that… that should be helpful.

432
01:10:40.800 --> 01:10:41.919
Moe Raine: Perfect, thank you.

433
01:10:41.920 --> 01:10:42.710
David Thomson: You're welcome.

434
01:10:48.770 --> 01:10:52.950
David Thomson: Well, with no other questions, I want to say it's a real pleasure that

435
01:10:53.220 --> 01:10:58.680
David Thomson: You guys were able to join tonight. Really… …

436
01:10:59.010 --> 01:11:01.380
David Thomson: You know, glad to present this topic.

437
